{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493279","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493279"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:03:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:03:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1274"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1274","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1274"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.06,0.06,0.69,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1274"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54262"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1274","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1274"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1274"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39762"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"476"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1254"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2545"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3835"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3974"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10819"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16215"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54262","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54262"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 18-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner with a one-week history of significant fatigue, malaise and sore throat. He denies recent travel, intravenous drug use or exposure to sick contacts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 120/70mmHg, respiratory rate 19/min and temperature 38.5\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. His chest is clear on auscultation. Exudates are present on both tonsils. Cervical lymphadenopathy is present bilaterally. There is fullness and mild tenderness in the left upper quadrant of his abdomen.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["HIV Ag/Ab testing","Abdominal ultrasound","Anti-viral therapy","Reassurance and supportive therapy","Amoxycillin for one week"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a one-week history of fever, pharyngitis, and lymphadenopathy which is the classic triad of infectious mononucleosis (IM). This condition rarely requires specific therapy and is typically treated with \u003Cstrong\u003Ereassurance, clinical observation, and supportive therapy. \u003C/strong\u003EWhilst other upper respiratory tract infections both viral and bacterial may also present with fever, lymphadenopathy and pharyngitis, it is less commonly associated with the presumed splenomegaly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInfectious mononucleosis is a contagious illness resulting from Epstein-Barr virus (HHV-4) infection. The Epstein-Barr virus (EBV) enters the host and replicates in the oropharynx lymphoid tissue for between four to eight weeks before symptoms appear. Classic features include pharyngitis, fever, atypical lymphocytosis (on blood smear) and lymphadenopathy (affecting the posterior cervical nodes more commonly than the anterior cervical nodes). Despite these classic features, the diagnosis should be confirmed with a heterophile antibody test or via EBV serology. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to confirm the diagnosis of EBV as it is pertinent to confirm the diagnosis to exclude the possibility of bacterial tonsillitis (which may benefit from antibiotic treatment) and to advise patients of the risks associated with IM (i.e., splenic rupture, airway obstruction, \u003Cem\u003Eo\u003C/em\u003Er excessive fatigue). Should the investigations for suspected EBV/IM not confirm the diagnosis, consideration should be given to treat pharyngitis where appropriate. IM is generally a self-limited condition and no specific treatment is required, the mainstay of therapy is supportive care (i.e., paracetamol or ibuprofen, hydration, rest, and avoidance of physical activity and strenuous activity for 3-4 weeks).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile acute HIV infection could present similarly, there were no mentioning of risk factors in the stem such as men who have sex with men (MSM), multiple sexual partners or intravenous drug use and \u003Cstrong\u003EHIV Ag/Ab testing \u003C/strong\u003Eis unnecessary at this stage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst an \u003Cstrong\u003Eabdominal ultrasound \u003C/strong\u003Eexamination may confirm the presence of splenomegaly in this case, it is not going to change management. If the patient was keen to take part in contact sports, it then might be prudent to do an ultrasound so that the patient can be given advice on the timing of resolve of returning to such physical activities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe efficacy of \u003Cstrong\u003Eantivirals \u003C/strong\u003E(i.e., acyclovir) in IM is controversial, and the quality of evidence is very low. Some clinicians opt for anti-viral medications in at-risk groups (i.e., immunocompromised). For a non-severe case, as above, antivirals are not recommended.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAntibiotics are not indicated for EBV infection. \u003Cstrong\u003EAmoxycillin \u003C/strong\u003Eand ampicillin can cause a rash not related to penicillin hypersensitivity when administered to a patient with EBV.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Infectious mononucleosis is generally a self-limited condition and no specific treatment is required, the mainstay of therapy is supportive."],"references":["Turabelisze, G., Infectious mononucleosis [Internet] bestpractice.bmj.com 2021 [cited 19 Sep 2021]. Available from \u003Chttps://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/123/pdf/123/Infectious%20mononucleosis.pdf\u003E","Aronson, M., Auwaerter, P., Infectious mononucleosis [Internet] www.uptodate.com 2021 [cited 19 Sep 2021]. Available from \u003Chttps://www.uptodate.com/contents/infectious-mononucleosis\u003E","Electronic Therapeutic Guidelines. 2021. Epstein\u2013Barr virus (EBV) infection. [online] [Accessed 19 September 2021] Available at: \u003Chttps://tgldcdp-tg-org-au.ezproxy.flinders.edu.au/viewTopic?topicfile=epstein-barr-virus\u0026guidelineName=Antibiotic#toc_d1e47\u003E","Australasian Society for HIV, Viral Hepatitis and Sexual Health Medicine (ASHM). 2021. Decision Making In HIV. [online] [Accessed 30th January 2024] Available at: https://ashm.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/ASHM-HIV-Decision-Making_FA_web.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39762"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1274"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39762","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39762"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-02T12:46:21+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-02T12:47:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1274"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54262"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.